# Rust: Prefer Shared Ownership Over Copies

In the data plane (`crates/core`, `crates/mixer`, `packages/bindings`), avoid unnecessary allocations and buffer copies.

## Defaults

- Wrap heavy objects in `Arc<T>` (`PeerConnection`, tracks, `DataChannel`, runtime state).
- Use `bytes::Bytes` for RTP payloads, DataChannel binary frames, and PCM sample data crossing API boundaries.
- Pass `&[u8]`, `Bytes`, or `Arc<[u8]>` into send/write methods; only copy when an downstream API requires ownership and no shared handle exists.
- Prefer borrowing in hot paths (`&str`, `&[u8]`, `&SessionDescription`) and clone only at FFI/serialization boundaries (NAPI, JSON).

## Patterns

```rust
// ✅ GOOD — share payload, no extra Vec
pub struct DataChannelMessage {
    pub is_string: bool,
    pub data: Bytes,
}

pub async fn send_binary(&self, data: Bytes) -> Result<(), CoreError> {
    self.inner.send(&data).await?;
    Ok(())
}

// ❌ BAD — unconditional copy on every message
pub async fn send_binary(&self, data: &[u8]) -> Result<(), CoreError> {
    self.inner.send(&Bytes::copy_from_slice(data)).await?;
    Ok(())
}
```

```rust
// ✅ GOOD — caller reuses Arc track handle
pub fn as_track_local(&self) -> Arc<dyn TrackLocal + Send + Sync> {
    Arc::clone(&self.inner)
}
```

## Where copies are acceptable

- NAPI boundary (JS `Buffer` ↔ Rust) — one copy each direction is expected.
- SDP/ICE JSON serialization for signaling.
- Small config structs and error strings.

## Event handlers

- Forward `Bytes` or `Arc`-wrapped handles through channels; do not `.to_vec()` unless the consumer needs a mutable owned buffer.
